Oil prices dropped despite Hurricane Rita approaching the Gulf of Mexico, as OPEC vowed to increase crude supply if needed.
The organization committed to releasing an additional two million barrels per day from October 1, maintaining the production ceiling at 28 million barrels per day.
Hurricane Rita intensified to a category two storm with winds of 160 km/h, prompting flight suspensions and evacuations.
Louisiana and Texas prepared for the hurricane's impact, with thousands of Katrina survivors being relocated to safer areas.
Galveston issued a mandatory evacuation, while New Orleans braced for potential flooding and damage.
